      • Active Minds Student Chapter at CAMHS

        Department Sponsored Student Organization

        Website Mission

        Contact: Hannah Niederriter, Selorna Ackuayi, Seth Rosenberg, Email group officers

        Group Not Registered Yet

        Mission
        Active Minds @ Harvard/CAMHS, is a peer education group under the umbrella of Harvard University Health Services (HUHS) that acts as liaisons between Counseling and Mental Health Services (CAMHS) and the Harvard College community. We work collaboratively with CAMHS, the Harvard administration, and student communities to promote awareness of issues and improve accessibility to resources related to mental health and wellness. In an effort to do so, we strive to reduce stigma surrounding mental health and engage in outreach to address the specific needs of various communities on campus.

        We strive to encourage open conversation about matters of mental health and educate students about resources on campus. Ultimately, we hope to help the community to better understand issues of emotional well-being, recognize signs of students in distress, and feel comfortable navigating resources for support.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • Advocating Success for Kids

        Public Service

        Website Mission

        Mission
        Advocating Success for Kids (ASK) is a primary care clinic at Boston Children’s Hospital designed for children with behavioral and learning disabilities. Our ASK club aligns with this clinic; members serve as advocates for patient families. Our mission is to support the ASK clinic and its patients through advocacy work.

        Harvard undergraduates serve as Advocates. They not only have the opportunity to shadow physicians in the ASK Clinic, but also serve patient families as well. Advocates provides a great deal of support to families including access to social and educational resources and an alternative line of communication to the Clinic. Advocates fill a key gap in the healthcare services that families of the ASK Clinic receive.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • Asian Student Arts Project

        Creative and Performing Arts

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Nikhil Kamat, Avery Hansberger, Email group officers

        Mission
        The purpose of ASAP is to provide the network and resources for Pan-Asian and Pan-Asian-American students across multiple disciplines including theater, film, dance, music, comedy, writing, entertainment, media, and more to make art and create a community for these artists.

        ASAP aims to celebrate the community, experience, culture, and history of Asian students at Harvard with events such as group discussions, movie screenings, workshops, open-mic nights, group outings, panels, and large- and small-scale performances and theatrical productions.

        Membership Benefits
        The membership benefits include being part of a community of Pan-Asian student artists on campus. We meet weekly for brunch on Saturdays, plan events and outings together, and ultimately serve as friends and supporters for members who want to create art together.

        Lifetime membership

      • Association of Black Harvard Women

        Women's Initiatives

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Let us act as a catalyst in bringing Black women and other gender marginalized students on Harvard University's campus together for academic, cultural, political, and social purposes. Let us find strength, support, and courage in our unity and combine our intellect, spirit, and resources so that we may best address the needs and problems of Black gender marginalized students at Harvard College and within the University as a whole. Let us be actively engaged in the larger discourse on gender marginalized issues, particularly those pertaining to Black gender marginalized people, on Harvard University's campus, nationwide, and worldwide and contribute our energies to these causes. Lastly, let us maintain an interest and commitment to the overall Black experience, both within and outside of the Harvard community.

        The Association of Black Harvard Women will firmly commit to the works of anti-racism and gender inclusivity, while welcoming and celebrating the stories of all gender marginalized people. We will also uplift the voices of the Black queer community and engage in unwavering activism by condemning injustices on—and off—campus. Finally, we will advocate for the end of rape culture, sexual assault, and sexual harassment on and beyond campus, prioritizing the safety and well-being of survivors.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • Bengali Association of Students at Harvard College

        Cultural and Racial Initiatives

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Bengali Association of Students at Harvard (BASHA) is a cultural organization concerned with promoting the unique aspects of Bengali culture and fostering community among students with roots in Bangladesh, West Bengal, and the diaspora, as well as others with interest in the region’s rich history and traditions.       • Black Arts Collective

        Cultural and Racial Initiatives

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Black Arts Collective works to address the on-campus social and systemic issues of how Black artistic and creative expression is too commonly disregarded by general art communities and derailed by those made uncomfortable by its presence. We build affinity through artistry by hosting events and makerspaces that center healing and joy as a method of collective liberation.

        Our makerspaces provide a safe space for Black students to create, regardless of skill level and experience, for various creative disciplines, including but not limited to dance, painting, writing, photography, film, music, multimedia, and performance art. Our events are fun activities for everyone in the community to participate in, regardless of any interest in the arts. These include things such as parties, speaker events, art festivals, concerts, and workshops. We plan to have an annual showcase/festival of local Black artists including spoken word poetry, short films, dance performances, and original plays.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • Brattle Street Chamber Players

        Creative and Performing Arts

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The mission of the Brattle Street Chamber Players is to perform string orchestra and chamber music at a professional level while exploring and promoting a greater understanding of both traditional and contemporary repertoire that is largely inaccessible to more traditional Harvard orchestras. Without a music director or conductor, we are committed to upholding the ideals of musical democracy, with logistical and musical endeavors solely led by student members. Our goal is to create an inclusive and collaborative community where all members can grow as musicians and contribute to the vibrant musical community of Harvard and beyond.

      • CityStep

        Public Service

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        CityStep is a team of Harvard undergraduates who all share a passion for the arts, community service, and youth empowerment. Harvard CityStep was the first branch of what is now a growing 501(c)3 not-for-profit. For going on 39 years, Harvard CityStep has strove to be a partner to the Cambridge Public Schools, offering a free arts education to students in the 5th, 6th, and 7th grade. Throughout every CityStep year, our students (aka CitySteppers!) explore dance, theater, music, and more to develop both performance and personal skills! Traditionally, this culminates in an end-of-year show! CityStep is open to the entire Cambridge community, the end-of-year performance brings together all CitySteppers within our program to showcase the work our students do year-round: collaborative art making, thoughtful engagement of real-world themes, and individual expression!

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • Conflux

        Creative and Performing Arts

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Peggy Yin

        Mission
        As technology continues to advance and play an increasingly central role in our lives, the intersection of art and technology helps us understand the complex and rapidly changing relationship between humanity and technology. Through researching, critiquing, and developing cross-disciplinary, innovative media that integrates technological development with artistic practice, the Conflux collective (confluxcollective.org) aims to expand the intersection of contemporary art and cutting-edge technology, pushing both towards a synergistic responsible, inclusive, and humane future. Conflux provides a supportive ecosystem for artists to challenge and critique the dominant narratives and power structures that shape our society, and for technologists to consider the ethical and social implications of their work. Moreover, through creating large-scale, participatory installations, Conflux practices what it means for humans and technology to create together.

        Membership Benefits
        By joining Conflux, you’ll be part of a cross-disciplinary, highly collaborative team passionate about expanding the art tech scene at Harvard and beyond. You’ll have an exciting opportunity to learn about and investigate how the latest technology can be used meaningfully and artistically. You’ll work on imagining and developing methods and mediums specifically for art tech practice. You’ll help pave the way for how media and technology can help artists bring their visions into the world.

        Lifetime membership

      • Datamatch

        College Life

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Datamatch’s mission is to help students find love and friendship on their campus. We run Harvard’s (and other universities’) Datamatch tradition, which include an annual matchmaking survey, dates, and other events to encourage students to meet each other within their student body. In the fall, we also run a matching survey for first-years to meet each other once they get on campus, and in the spring, we collaborate with the Senior Class Committee to run the Match series of senior matchmaking.

        Membership Benefits
        Datamatch offers members the opportunity to gain professional skills by contributing to a global event with over 50,000 participants each year. Members join one of five teams (Algo, Stats, Design, Web, Business) and are able to contribute to the Datamatch website, events, and overall cultural phenomenon by the spring semester. Members also become part of a close-knit community on campus.

        Lifetime membership

        Department Sponsored Student Organization

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Gwen Koch, Email group officers

        Mission
        The Food Literacy Project (FLP), is HUDS' food education initiative. With focuses on sustainability, nutrition, food preparation and community, the FLP seeks to empower everyone to make informed food choices. Every undergraduate house/dining hall has a fellow; FLP also has a presence at GSAS.

        Membership Benefits
        -Expanded knowledge about the food system.
        -Demonstrable experience in event planning, budgeting and marketing.
        -Volunteer and hands-on experience with local food organizations.

      • Friends of Project Sunshine

        Public Service

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        Friends of Project Sunshine at Harvard College’s mission is to give Harvard undergraduates the opportunity to bring programming - recreation (arts), educational (tutoring and mentoring) and social service (HIV and nutritional counseling) - to children facing medical challenges and their families in the Boston area and beyond, by partnering with the Project Sunshine Project, which extends across 175 major cities across the United States and in four international satellite sites: Canada, China, Israel, and Kenya. Friends of Project Sunshine at Harvard College would focus on free services for medically challenged children and their families in the greater Boston area.

      • Harvard African Students Association

        The Harvard African Students' Association, founded in 1977, is an organization committed to nourishing cultural, intellectual, political, and economic awareness about the African continent.         Mission
        The Classical Club provides a wide variety of opportunities for enthusiasts of ancient Rome, Greece, and their corresponding languages and cultures to promote and celebrate the Classics. The club's activities include, but are not limited to, monthly dinners, classically-themed movie nights, the translation and production of a Greek or Latin play for the wider audience on campus, and the occasional toga party. The club also sponsors Persephone, a journal for undergraduate scholarship, translation, creative writing, and art inspired by the Classics. During the spring semester, club members organize and host the Harvard Certamen, a Classics-based quiz-bowl-style tournament for high school students that attracts schools from across the nation. Excitingly, in Fall 2023, we will begin formal planning for our Spring 2024 production of Seneca’s Medea!

      • Harvard College German Students Association

        Cultural and Racial Initiatives

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Harvard College German Students Association provides a welcoming and supportive space for students with a German educational or cultural background in order to share experiences of American culture and as Harvard students, including discussions of specific challenges associated with being a German Harvard College student, such as the transition from a German educational system to an American one.
        HCGSA thus focuses on welcoming Harvard freshmen and exchange students from German universities by providing them with a network of students who have gone through a similar process and on whom they can rely for advice and support in administrative, cultural, and social matters.
        The Association helps German students stay in touch with their home country by having a home community away from home, while fully involved in their life at Harvard. Additionally, the Association serves as a forum for discussion about German politics, current events, and the like. To fulfill this mission, HCGSA will hold welcoming events for newcomers at the beginning of the school year, pairing them with upperclassmen, as much as possible from a similar background, and familiarizing them with the broader Harvard campus and with Cambridge and Boston. Bi-weekly dinners will foster a sense of community and provide a supportive network for all members. We also aim to build a strong alumni network of German Harvard College graduates. HCGSA graduates could then help current college students plan for future academic and professional opportunities back in Germany or Europe in general.

        Mission
        Founded in 1969, the Harvard Political Review (HPR) is an undergraduate-run journal of politics, policy, and culture. The review addresses domestic and international affairs, as well as political discourse on campus. It also conducts interviews with political figures and experts ranging from Alan Derschowitz to Anthony Fauci to Kara Swisher. Aside from the standard publication route, students are encouraged to participate in a wide variety of programs including the Red Line Investigative Fellowship, the Summer Fellowship, and Columns. They can also pitch topic ideas for and contribute to our quarterly magazine. Previous issues include “Isolation” (Fall 2020), “Girls Girls Girls” (Winter 2019), “Engineering Earth” (Fall 2018), and “Body Politic” (Summer 2014).

        Mission
        The purpose of the Harvard Program for International Education shall be to create and foster interest in international relations in high school students, especially those from local schools.       • Harvard Undergraduate Beekeepers

        Hobbies and Special Interests

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        We started with an idea in the Harvard Community Garden, but have since become an independent club. In the past, we have partnered with the Food Literacy Project to bring bees into the important farm to table picture, and the Health Advocacy Project with a small honey-tasting event.

        Since 2006, honeybee colonies in the US have seen collapse rates of up to 90%. As key pollinators, honeybees are directly responsible for cultivation of over 30% of the most important food crops. HUB seeks to stimulate active discussion on campus about not only the plight of the honeybee, but also to educate about the incredible world of apiculture. We would seek to bring together groups with important stakes in the fate of beekeeping. From all parts of the Harvard community, from the RoboBees Laboratory designing robots that mimic hive behavior at the School of Engineering & Applied Sciences, to the Environmental Exposure biologists working to link between declining bee health and pesticides at the School of Public Health.

        4. The BCL should be a unified voice to outside the Black Community. There should be strength in numbers. The BCL should work together on initiatives of importance on campus.

      • Harvard Undergraduate Medical Humanities Forum

        Academic and Pre-Professional

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Harvard Ungergraduate Medical Humanities Forum strives to foster a community in which undergraduates who are interested in the medical humanities can collectively explore their academic interests and passions. It will create opportunities for students to engage in critical discussion with each other about medical humanities scholarship and also host events in which students can learn from faculty members and healthcare practitioners involved in the medical humanities field. Importantly, the Medical Humanities Forum will encourage students to collectively reflect on how pre-medical and pre-health experiences relate to their future practice of medicine or other health-related fields. For instance, it will encourage students to explore the often-overlooked question of how humanities studies can prepare aspiring clinicians to treat patients - a responsibility that requires not only scientific knowledge but also the very human ability to engage patients as people. Students in the Forum will discuss essential questions like this one during weekly meetings and in their writing. To provide an outlet for student voices in the medical humanities, the Forum will maintain an online publication of creative writing, in which students can publish works about the pre-medical and pre-health experiences or about their more general experiences with suffering, illness, and healing. The Forum will also publish on an online blog, in which students can post interviews with medical humanities faculty and healthcare professionals as well as updates about the medical humanities field. Through the scholarship of dedicated students guided by faculty and physicians, the newly emerging medical humanities field has the opportunity to grow and develop on Harvard's campus.

        Academic and Pre-Professional

        Website Mission

        Contact: Michael Gomez, Yana Lazarova-Weng, Email group officers

        Mission
        The two aims of the Harvard Psychedelics club:

        Our first aim is to educate the general public about the current research going on in the field of psychedelics as well as highlight the role that psychedelics have played in culture and society over time.

        Our second aim is to advocate for the decriminalization of psychedelic medicines and the increased accessibility of psychedelic medicines for those who need them.

        We are not blindly encouraging the use of psychedelics, instead, we are convinced by the promising research that has shown the ability of psychedelics to effectively treat seemingly intractable conditions such as Post Traumatic Stress Disorder [MDMA], Treatment Resistant Depression [Psilocybin], and Addiction [Psilocybin], and we believe that making them more accessible for measured and responsible usage could help millions of people and our society at large.

      • Harvard Undergraduate Women Entrepreneurship

        Women's Initiatives

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Josefine Hasbo, Email group officers

        Mission
        The mission of Women Entrepreneurship (WE) club at Harvard is to create a supportive and thoughtful environment where women at Harvard can develop the skills and ideas necessary to pursue their entrepreneurial interests to drive positive change in the world. Every woman has the capacity to be creative, every woman has the ability to bring their ideas to light, and every woman has the courage to be a leader and enact change in their communities. But despite our potential for greatness, women are significantly underrepresented in entrepreneurship, half as likely to become entrepreneurs than men, and are often unable to secure the same funding or support as that of men; that’s where WE come in. Rooted in three foundational pillars - building a supportive community, empowering women to follow their entrepreneurial passions, and inspiring future generations of women entrepreneurs to drive change - WE aims to provide women with the knowledge and resources to enhance their skills in important entrepreneurial areas such as leadership, networking, pitching ideas, storytelling, creative thinking, fundraising, teamwork, and business communication.

        Through weekly lectures with leading women entrepreneurs, workshops, community dinners and social events, WE hopes to inspire and empower women at Harvard to discover their entrepreneurial drive, find their cofounders, and create change in areas they are passionate about. Built on the diversity of women from all backgrounds, WE will form the foundation for a community of women entrepreneurs who will one day become the new voices of entrepreneurship.

        Membership Benefits
        Members can attend our lectures and our limited-spot dinners with founders and investors. Members have access to a community of women who are interested in entrepreneurship.

      • Harvard-Radcliffe Orchestra

        Creative and Performing Arts

        Website Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Harvard-Radcliffe Orchestra (HRO) is Harvard’s premier symphonic orchestra, an official 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization, and also the oldest symphony orchestra in America, tracing its roots to the founding of the Harvard Pierian Sodality in 1808. As both a student-run organization and a class in Harvard’s Department of Music, HRO gives qualified instrumentalists the opportunity to continue performing orchestral music at a very high level throughout their college career, while also building friendships with other student musicians at Harvard. Public performances and community outreach events allow the ensemble to demonstrate recent projects in a manner that also benefits the Greater Boston community. HRO also offers considerable exposure to music administration and leadership; a student board leads the orchestra in concert and rehearsal logistics, publicity, alumni outreach, financial matters, social events, and tours, with support from the Alumni Foundation, Office for the Arts, Music Department, and Memorial Hall staff. Course logistics concerning repertoire, space bookings, and ringers are decided in collaboration with the Music Director and Teaching Fellows. Students therefore have the opportunity to grow in both artistic and bureaucratic skill and have a significant voice in how the organization is run.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

        Mission
        The mission of Omo Naija x The Wahala Boys is to educate the members of the greater Harvard community through dance and its role in the culture of the Afro-Caribbean.       • PBHA's Chinatown Big Sibling Program

        PBHA

        Website Mission

        Contact: Justin Chen

        Mission
        Chinatown Big Sib is a one-to-one mentorship program run by Harvard College students with the Phillips Brooks House Association. The program offers young children ages 6 to 12 years from the Boston Chinatown neighborhood a unique experience with getting to know and spending time with college students from the area. Our college student volunteers, or “Big Sibs”, are responsible for organizing one-on-one outings with their “Little Sibs” every other weekend. With these meetings and interactions, the program strives to build a strong relationship between Sib pairings. Big Sibs may take on the role of a mentor in academic, social, emotional context, or simply whatever best provides for their Little Sibs. This program runs full year, where Sib pairings remain the same throughout both semesters unless other arrangements are made.

        Mission
        The Harvard Undergraduate Legal Committee (HULC) gets students excited about legal aid, public interest law, and public service through volunteering with pro bono organizations throughout the Greater Boston Area and consistent programming that educates members on the pathways to and impact of legal advocacy.

      • Student Astronomers at Harvard-Radcliffe

        Hobbies and Special Interests

        Website Mission

        Contact: Casey Murray, Kane Sjoberg, Email group officers

        Mission
        STAHR is focused on providing students the opportunity to learn about and engage in recreational astronomy. STAHR also seeks to promote interest in science and foster a healthy, inclusive community centered around our common interests. STAHR provides students with education in recreational astronomy with its Telescope Training Classes at the Loomis-Michael Observatory. Students who successfully complete the semester-long class receive HUID card access to the Loomis-Michael Observatory for the remainder of their degree program at Harvard University. STAHR is committed to offering advanced instruction in observational astronomy subjects, including, but not limited to astrophotography, to further students’ knowledge in the field. STAHR is committed to holding community events, including its semesterly dark sky trips, open house observatory nights, and movie nights. In addition, STAHR is committed to helping the student community learn about opportunities in astronomy through initiatives including, but not limited to, speaking engagements with professionals in the sciences.

      • The Harvard Foundation

        Office

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        In 1981, the president and deans of Harvard University established the Harvard Foundation for Intercultural and Race Relations with the mandate to "improve relations among racial and ethnic groups within the University and to enhance the quality of our common life." In pursuit of this mission, the Foundation seeks to involve students of all racial, ethnic, and cultural backgrounds in the ongoing enterprises of the University. The Foundation sponsors annual programs and activities that are designed to promote interracial and intercultural awareness and understanding in the Harvard community, as well as to highlight the cultural contributions of students from all backgrounds.

        Membership Benefits
        The Harvard Foundation Student Advisory Committee, or SAC, is the student-group facing arm of the Harvard Foundation for Intercultural and Race Relations, founded in 1981. We achieve this through two core processes: 1) Grant disbursements, and 2) HFSAC Senator meetings. Any undergraduate student organizations officially recognized by Harvard College with a mission of improving race relations and promoting intercultural awareness and understanding may apply to join the Harvard Foundation Student Advisory Committee.

        Mission
        The mission of The Harvard Krokodiloes (hereafter “Krokodiloes”) is to spread the joy and the value of its music in the hopes of enriching the audiences’ and the members’ lives through the powers of human sharing. As Harvard’s oldest a cappella singing group, the Krokodiloes are a versatile group of twelve tuxedo-clad undergraduates who sing jazz, swing, ballads, and rock music from the 20th century and beyond to audiences all over the world.       • The Harvard Undergraduate Ichthus

        Religious and Spiritual Life

        Website Mission

        Mission
        The Harvard Ichthus is a journal of Christian thought. It exists for the purpose of fostering deep Christian thought among the members of the Harvard community, taking seriously the motto of Harvard University: “Veritas Christo et Ecclesiae,” in English “Truth for Christ and the Church.” It adopts these words of the Rev. Prof. Peter J. Gomes, preached at the Memorial Church, as its mission statement:

        "There is a rumor about, and fanned in certain quarters, that this University
        has long since abandoned its ancient motto and is conformable only
        to ‘Veritas.’ That simply is not true. The seal by which the President and
        Fellows of Harvard College continue to conduct their business is still the seal that says: ‘Veritas Christo et Ecclesiae.’ One cannot undo the past, and in this particular case one should not undo the past. The university-- and this University in particular-- is in the business of goodness and virtue
        personified, and not simply in the bottom lines of fairness and excellence.
        Christ and the Church were an essential part of that truth to which Harvard and the generations of its children were committed. ...Truth for Christ and the Church is not here by accident or by sufferance; it is here by design and intent. ...Indeed, as a symbol of Christian truth, we are here to remind
        Harvard of a dimension beyond its own self-interest and self-perception... We Christians must never forget, nor must we permit our College or our University ever to forget, that knowledge without virtue is a destructive danger that produces arrogant technocrats who are a danger to all that is holy, hopeful, lovely, and true, and who must be resisted. Our pious ancestors understood this, and thus they dedicated this small, fragile College in the wilderness to a truth that was seen in and for Christ and the Church. Veritas-- that is, true Veritas, and not simply correct information-- can never be separated from the one in whom it is most perfectly and fully seen: Jesus Christ. Not everyone may believe that, but those of us who do must not be intimidated by those who don't, and we must be emboldened to claim that truth not only as our own but as one that is essential to the definition of a University and College worthy of the name."

        (Strength for the Journey, pgs. 56, 60)

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • The Harvard Undergraduate Research Journal

        Media and Publications

        Website Mission

        Contact: Ellie Shin, Email group officers

        Mission
        We are an annual publication that promotes undergraduate research by publishing undergraduate research and highlighting relevant advancements in the scientific community of Harvard University. At its core, THURJ allows students to gain insight into the peer review process, which lies central to modern scientific investigation. All THURJ manuscripts are rigorously reviewed by the Peer Review Board (consisting of undergraduates at Harvard College), and the top selections are reviewed by Harvard graduate students, post-doctoral fellows, and professors. This process stimulates faculty-student collaboration and provides students with valuable feedback on their research; it also promotes collaboration between the College and Harvard’s many graduate and professional schools.

        The Oak Club

        Social Organization (RSO)

        Website Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The Oak Club strives to be a welcoming, inclusive, and supportive social community for its members. The Club provides an opportunity for students to make friendships across class-years and build community within Harvard outside of the fast pace of campus life. Members will be able to participate in an annual retreat, bi-weekly meals, the recruitment process, and various other social events. Any undergraduate student may be invited to become a member of the Oak Club, and upon invitation may choose to undergo a series of bonding activities with the new class. Engagement within the Oak Club does not end upon graduation, but instead continues with an extensive alumni community. The Club shall remain accessible to all who are eligible to join regardless of sexual orientation, gender-identity, race, ability, or financial circumstances.

        Membership Benefits
        Membership in the Oak Club includes access to a welcoming community, weekly social events, and bi-weekly dinners. It also includes membership in a post-graduate alumni community.

        Mission
        The River Charles Ensemble, Harvard’s premier conductor-less chamber orchestra, is dedicated to the highest quality of music-making and performance. Formed in the spring of 2012, the River Charles Ensemble is a community of musicians who believe in the power and application of chamber music techniques to solo and orchestral performances. The musicians of the River Charles Ensemble share a passion for this distinctive and innovative approach to music.
